WEBVTT

00:01.770 --> 00:14.490
It is July the 7th, and I'm in the Connolly building 
and have the pleasure and honor of chatting with

00:01.770 --> 00:14.490
Daniel Hernandez about his Texas A&M student 
experiences. Daniel, say a sentence to test your

00:14.670 --> 00:16.530
mic. Hello, I'm here, and I'm glad to be here with 
Haskell Monroe. Daniel, I want to introduce

00:22.460 --> 00:26.600
yourself to someone who may read the transcript or 
hear the tape. Daniel, describe briefly your

00:26.580 --> 00:41.340
family background, from where, when, and what 
brought you to this community, and where to high

00:26.580 --> 00:41.340
school, and so forth. My mom came originally from 
Mexico City. My dad was born in Hondo, Texas, and

00:46.240 --> 00:54.420
there's a 20 years difference between my mom and 
dad. My mom and dad... ...had met each other in

00:56.580 --> 01:00.240
Taylor, Texas. My mom's brothers and dad had come 
to Texas in the early part of the century, trying to

01:01.220 --> 01:14.260
find their way into a better situation. And they 
stayed here for about a year or two, then they sent

01:14.240 --> 01:26.400
for my mom and her mother and sisters, which has 
been the pattern for many, many years. And they

01:26.580 --> 01:31.600
came, and my dad met them. He was born in Texas, and 
by the time my dad met them, my dad had already been

01:31.780 --> 01:45.380
married three times, had three children from his 
prior marriage, and met my mom in Taylor, Texas.

01:45.880 --> 01:52.300
And then they married and moved to Wheelock, 
Texas, which is in Robertson County. And there, my

01:53.120 --> 01:56.380
mom and dad were involved in sharecropping. 
They're at the Seal Farm. And they were there for

02:00.580 --> 02:04.650
several years. All along this time, there was a 
gentleman by the name of Pablo Hernandez, who was a

02:04.630 --> 02:15.650
friend of my dad's, an older gentleman, much older 
than my dad. And he would always share the gospel

02:15.630 --> 02:23.650
with my dad about having a changed life, a new 
spiritual life. And my dad said that he would... He

02:26.630 --> 02:34.650
would humor him and go with him to the church 
functions because they had good cover dish

02:26.630 --> 02:34.650
dinners and suppers and lunches. And so he would do 
that on Sundays. And eventually something

02:37.630 --> 02:44.650
happened where it really caught hold of my dad 
spiritually, and it really transformed his life.

02:45.630 --> 02:52.650
This is important because this was the pivotal 
point that sort of began to make him think

02:45.630 --> 02:52.650
differently about himself and the family. As a 
result of this new way of thinking, a new thinking

02:53.630 --> 02:55.650
of himself, of the family. And by this time, I think 
there must have been about four children from my

02:57.630 --> 03:02.650
mom's... that mom had had with him. And he had his 
three other children, who by this time were

03:04.630 --> 03:09.650
already adults. And they were often married. But 
my dad decided to ask the owner of the land if he

03:12.630 --> 03:24.650
would drive my sister and drop her off at 
schoolhouse. My sister Isabel. And

03:25.630 --> 03:31.650
for some reason, the gentleman said no. Or it 
couldn't happen, it wouldn't happen, whatever.

03:35.630 --> 03:38.650
And so that really, really touched my dad. It just 
changed... He told me later that it was weird

03:40.630 --> 03:48.650
because had it been before he had had this 
transformed, new life, spiritual relationship

03:40.630 --> 03:48.650
with God, it would have just been one of those other 
setbacks. Plus, he said I probably wouldn't have

03:50.630 --> 03:53.650
even asked him. But he said... That night he went 
out to the cotton field and just sort of cried and

03:55.630 --> 04:01.650
just said, you know, there's got to be something 
better. And so somehow he just felt like there was a

04:01.630 --> 04:06.650
need to move. And so they, within a couple of weeks 
or so, picked up their stuff, made the decision and

04:06.630 --> 04:15.650
moved to Bryan, 20 miles away. And so they came to 
Bryan. And at that time, this is about in the 30s,

04:18.630 --> 04:25.060
late 30s, early 40s. My dad, having developed a 
real spiritual reawakening, he started working

04:26.040 --> 04:41.210
but also started preaching, having church 
services at his house. And so he would have church

04:41.190 --> 04:47.210
services and work at the Texas Highway Department 
and just little by little. And since agriculture

04:47.190 --> 04:55.210
was also part of his background, he began to obtain 
contracts with some of the local farmers and

04:47.190 --> 04:55.210
landowners. Landowners in the Brazos Bottom. And 
would contract labor to work in the fields. And

05:02.190 --> 05:10.400
that's what my brothers and I did all along for the 
most part of our younger life.

05:10.380 --> 05:20.400
My oldest brother, my oldest two brothers, and my 
sister, Isabelle, or all of my brothers and I

05:10.380 --> 05:20.400
finished high school at Bryan High. Which then 
used to be Stephen F. Austin in Bryan. Mm-hmm. My

05:24.832 --> 05:28.400
first sister, the first person in our family to 
finish school was my sister, Isabelle. Because

05:28.380 --> 05:39.400
there was no college here or A&M did not accept 
women, this was back in the early 50s, she went to

05:28.380 --> 05:39.400
Baldwin-McKinsey College. McKinsey-Bowen 
College, a business college here, a year program

05:39.380 --> 05:46.400
or something for secretarial training. And 
that's where my sister went. My older brothers, my

05:48.380 --> 05:53.400
older brother, Mike, finished high school 
probably about 15 years ago. Sometime around that

05:53.380 --> 05:58.400
time, 56. And he was 21 years old when he finished 
high school. And my brother, Andrew, who finished

06:01.380 --> 06:07.400
about a year later, two years later, was also 21. 
And the reason they ended up being 21 when he

06:07.380 --> 06:15.400
finished was because my dad would take them out 
from school and they would work the fields. During

06:15.380 --> 06:21.400
this interim, what they would end up doing is they 
would work the fields here and also go to Lubbock,

06:15.380 --> 06:21.400
Texas and work. And invariably sometimes there 
was a six months missed or a year missed, but they

06:21.380 --> 06:29.400
did miss a lot of school, so they were older 
students. And my brother, Mike, was the first one

06:29.380 --> 06:35.400
to start Texas A&M. And I would say that was 
probably like 1956, 57. And starting the Corps of

06:40.380 --> 06:42.400
Cadets. Right, and so you finished high school 
what year? I finished high school in 1969. Five

06:48.380 --> 06:50.400
brothers later. I was the last of ten children. And 
there were six boys and four girls. One of my

06:57.560 --> 07:01.580
sisters died when she was like two years old. And

07:01.560 --> 07:11.580
so my brother, Mike, started going to college 
right after high school. And at first it was a real

07:11.560 --> 07:18.580
struggle for my dad, though he wanted him to go to 
educated. But, you know, the reality started. He

07:21.560 --> 07:26.580
said in that there was less time for them to work 
with him and work the fields. Fortunately for him,

07:26.560 --> 07:31.580
he had a lot of other sons coming in along the line. 
So every two years there was a new child and it was

07:31.560 --> 07:34.580
six boys. So fortunately there was one of us 
becoming of age to be able to drive or work. So that

07:40.560 --> 07:42.580
made it easier. But my dad had to find a new 
definition of what I guess one would call a man.

07:47.560 --> 07:50.580
Because in his mind, a man was someone who worked 
with his hands. Was sweating. Was always out in the

07:52.398 --> 07:54.580
fields. And now his sons, who he admired a lot, were 
now in a clean shirt, no sweat. It was working and

08:03.560 --> 08:07.580
trying to go to college. Even though while they 
were going to college they did work at the

08:07.560 --> 08:12.580
international shoe factory here. But it was a 
different kind. And I think at first my dad had, it

08:15.560 --> 08:19.580
was tough for him because it was this whole notion 
that, they were becoming not that rugged person

08:19.560 --> 08:27.580
that he was accustomed to them being. Even though 
they had lived through that for the most of their

08:27.560 --> 08:31.580
lives. At about what age did you become aware that 
college would be expected of you? I would say when I

08:36.560 --> 08:44.240
was probably about eight or nine years old. And 
it's interesting because we would still work in

08:44.220 --> 08:47.240
the cotton fields. We would go to the migrant 
workers. We would go into Lubbock and Brownfield,

08:49.220 --> 08:52.240
Texas. We would leave like in late May, spend all 
through August chopping cotton. And my dad would

08:59.220 --> 09:01.240
take the whole family with us. And then we would 
come back for about a month. And then late

09:05.220 --> 09:10.240
September we would go back to the same farm and then 
pick the cotton. And I remember when I was probably

09:10.220 --> 09:18.580
about nine years old, I began to sign my name, 
Daniel Hernandez, class of 73. Now that, I

09:23.840 --> 09:28.860
remember the teachers thought of thinking that 
funny. But my brothers were going to school. And I

09:32.840 --> 09:38.860
remember telling my, the teachers in Lockville, 
excuse me, I forgot the name of the school

09:38.840 --> 09:46.570
where I went to. But we would tell them. I would tell 
them I have brothers that were Aggies. And of

09:51.550 --> 09:56.570
course it was incongruent because she knew we were 
farm workers. But I think one time I came with an

09:56.550 --> 10:03.570
Aggie t-shirt and might have. Right. Now you left 
here before the spring semester was over to go

10:03.952 --> 10:10.010
work. Well, normally we were right after school. 
Right after school. All right. And then in the fall

10:13.740 --> 10:16.010
you'd be picking cotton. Right. And would you all 
just be absent from work? Were you absent from the

10:18.990 --> 10:20.011
Bryan schools? We were absent from the Bryan 
schools. And my dad would enroll us in Lubbock in

10:21.990 --> 10:28.640
the schools, but sometimes he would keep us about 
two or three weeks when we first got there because

10:32.620 --> 10:35.640
he needed us to get him started. And so then we'd go 
for about a month, a month and a half, and then he'd

10:38.620 --> 10:42.640
pull us out about two or three weeks before the 
semester was over. Okay. So we ended up going to

10:43.390 --> 10:45.640
school about six weeks. And at the front end, 
missing three weeks. At the back end, another

10:48.620 --> 10:50.640
three weeks. And so none of us ever failed. We all 
made the grade and made good grades over there and

10:52.620 --> 10:57.640
made good grades here. And my brother Mike, who was 
the first one to go through this whole process, was

11:01.620 --> 11:04.640
the one that really just drove it into us. You've 
got to study. We couldn't. My mom was very, very

11:07.026 --> 11:15.640
faithful to the Bible and would not let us read 
funny books. So at home we could not read funny

11:15.620 --> 11:17.640
books. We either had to be reading the Bible. We 
were one of the first to get a television here in

11:20.620 --> 11:25.640
Bryan, and I guess in 1956 we must have gotten the 
first TV. But we could not watch TV during the week.

11:34.620 --> 11:38.670
My brother would not let us watch TV during the week 
because we had to and we couldn't read funny books.

11:40.650 --> 11:42.670
So we left the Bible. And so on weekends we could 
watch TV. When I became a sophomore in high school,

11:50.650 --> 11:53.670
my older brother then, who was now at home, because 
every time one would leave, another brother would

11:53.650 --> 11:58.080
take over, my brother David would let us watch one 
hour of TV a night. Now, did those brothers assume a

12:04.060 --> 12:11.080
fatherly role? Were they the male rule enforcer?

12:17.060 --> 12:20.080
My dad was the ultimate enforcer. But if it ever got 
to him, it's because things were pretty bad. And so

12:24.060 --> 12:28.080
we never wanted to have things get to my dad. But the 
way my dad reared us was that if your older brother

12:28.060 --> 12:34.080
is there, he's in charge. And so my dad was working a 
lot, and so that was the way it was. If my brother

12:38.060 --> 12:43.080
that was two years older than me was there and I was 
10 and he was 12, he was the guy that I had to obey.

12:45.060 --> 12:50.080
What might have been the punishment if you had 
broken some of those rules? Probably

12:50.060 --> 12:57.510
a good whacking in the bottom. Though I'll have to 
admit, my dad was very lenient on me, and he kind of

13:02.490 --> 13:04.510
did and spanked me, and my other brothers weren't 
too crazy about that. But my brothers were the ones

13:07.490 --> 13:10.510
that put the fear in me. Because my dad may not have 
spanked me, but my brother Mike always had a belt

13:14.490 --> 13:17.510
around his chair, and he said, You see this belt 
right here? Do you want some of that belt? And of

13:21.490 --> 13:23.510
course I said no. And every once in a while I might 
cry mercy for my dad, but my brothers were pretty

13:26.490 --> 13:31.510
much the ones that were the disciplinarians. So 
now you graduate high school what year? 1969. And

13:35.078 --> 13:41.510
do you remember what part of the year you applied 
for admission to A&M? No, it was probably in the

13:41.490 --> 13:43.510
spring. I was pretty nervous because I was the last 
one to have started A&M, and I got admitted. And I

13:52.490 --> 13:55.510
was nervous when I started in September because I 
kind of felt a burden on me because I thought, Here

13:59.490 --> 14:01.510
all my brothers have gone. By that time I think two 
or three had already graduated, and the others

14:04.490 --> 14:06.510
were still in school. And it was like, Am I going to 
make it? And of course it was more of a, I wanted to

14:13.490 --> 14:17.510
make sure that I did as good as they had. Now your 
senior class at Stephen F. Austin, about how many?

14:23.490 --> 14:25.793
400 students. Okay. And was there a large number of 
them going to A&M? You know, I

14:30.490 --> 14:35.490
don't know how many. I know a lot of my classmates 
did. Percentage-wise I couldn't tell you. But you

14:40.470 --> 14:42.490
had a number of acquaintances. Oh yes, I had a 
number of acquaintances. All right. Did you have

14:46.483 --> 14:50.490
one or two close buddies that were going to A&M? 
Yeah. I had two or three friends of mine that I had

14:51.537 --> 14:56.490
played ball with, David Scasta and Ronald Spees.

15:01.470 --> 15:04.490
These were guys that I had gone to elementary 
school with, junior high and high school, and

15:04.470 --> 15:08.490
pretty bright guys, and they ended up coming to A&M 
also. All right. Can you describe now the routine

15:12.196 --> 15:16.490
of registering and going to your first classes, 
the first year? Well, I remember registering was

15:19.500 --> 15:25.730
just pretty straightforward, and I remember 
getting a letter of admission, and I guess by the

15:29.710 --> 15:34.730
time I was going to school, for me to go to A&M was 
important, but it was not one of those things that

15:38.800 --> 15:41.820
people jumped up and down, because it was expected 
of me. I was just doing the next thing in line, and so

15:45.800 --> 15:48.820
not that it lost its flavor, it was just it was 
expected. I guess my first days of class, I

15:54.800 --> 15:57.820
remember not feeling nervous, but just feeling 
excited about going to school. I did see some of my

16:00.800 --> 16:03.820
friends in some of our bigger classes, like 
history and English. Where was registration held

16:05.800 --> 16:07.820
then, Sebesa or G. Raleigh? Hmm. Because wasn't 
this still the time when you stood in line and went

16:13.430 --> 16:15.450
from counter to counter? Yeah, you had to go to 
counter to counter. I don't remember, quite

16:17.430 --> 16:19.450
frankly. You don't remember any unusual? No. 
Okay. No, it was pretty straightforward. Now, you

16:24.430 --> 16:26.450
lived at home. I lived at home as my brothers had 
before me. Did you encounter any kind of

16:30.430 --> 16:39.450
experiences that first fall, being a minority 
student, or anything else? No. No, I didn't. I

16:44.740 --> 16:49.760
think because, I mean, I had played around on 
campus. I had watched Randy Madsen set the world

16:49.740 --> 16:53.760
record. I rode my bike over here. So I was like at 
home. What I think I found that was kind of unusual

17:01.740 --> 17:04.820
is some of the students were not used to seeing a lot 
of Hispanics going to school, and I think for them

17:07.800 --> 17:09.820
it was kind of, it was just a difference. No one ever 
said negative, derogatory things, but there was a

17:17.800 --> 17:23.820
sense of disconnectedness with some of the 
students. But as far as a campus or feeling a part of

17:25.800 --> 17:29.820
the campus, that was something I always felt a part 
of the campus, and it was always, you know, as far as

17:32.800 --> 17:35.820
I was concerned, you know, that was my campus. I'd 
been there since I was a kid. Now, you have always

17:38.800 --> 17:42.820
struck me as being a person I would call a 
mainstreamer, that instead of being on the

17:44.800 --> 17:46.820
outside, you've always tried to be on the inside. 
Was that deliberate with you? Did you think about

17:51.800 --> 17:54.820
that, or was that just normal? You mean regarding 
just the political concepts or ideas related?

17:59.800 --> 18:02.820
Well, that was just part of my family upbringing. I 
think having been a part of the United Methodist

18:02.800 --> 18:06.820
Church taught us a lot. Taught us a lot of 
leadership skills. All my brothers and I were

18:10.800 --> 18:13.820
leaders in church conferences, which included 
several hundred students and youth, and we were

18:17.800 --> 18:20.820
always doing public speaking. We were always in 
the middle, always expected to be in the middle.

18:24.800 --> 18:28.820
And so there was an expectation among the 
Hernandez boys and girls to be in the middle and to

18:28.800 --> 18:32.820
participate. So when coming here, I ended up 
pursuing some of the same kind of activities. Can

18:38.800 --> 18:42.000
you share any recollections of that first 
semester of classes? What did you take? From whom?

18:45.933 --> 18:48.000
Any experiences? Oh, I remember taking a class 
from my

18:47.980 --> 18:57.190
freshman math class from, you may have to help me 
here, he's at A&M right now as their assistant

19:00.170 --> 19:05.190
provost. Bill Perry? No, the guy who handles all 
the fiscal affairs. I

19:09.170 --> 19:14.670
forget his name. He was my math professor in 
Algebra 102. And then they threw in all of the

19:18.650 --> 19:23.670
engineers along with all the social science and 
liberal arts. And of course I was there, I was doing

19:26.650 --> 19:29.670
well, because I had done well in high school, but I 
was with a bunch of engineers who could just eat

19:33.650 --> 19:35.670
that math up. And that was, you know, that was the 
first time I really was facing the idea of making a C

19:38.650 --> 19:45.670
in math. And it kind of like shocked me, because it 
wasn't that I didn't understand it, it was just the

19:50.740 --> 19:52.760
material was going faster than I had been used to, 
because these kids were picking it up a lot faster.

19:57.740 --> 19:59.760
I had my English teacher, I remember this quite 
vividly and I forget her name, but it was the year

20:02.760 --> 20:06.780
that Midnight Cowboy came out. And the first 
English paper, my brothers had told me, the first

20:09.760 --> 20:11.780
paper you write, you're going to probably make an F 
on it, because they're going to write it up and

20:15.760 --> 20:18.780
you're going to just, like, you don't know how to 
write. Well, that's what happened. I mean, I wrote

20:19.760 --> 20:21.780
it, I think I made a D, barely made a D. And then my 
teacher talked to me, and so we were supposed to

20:25.760 --> 20:30.780
write a narrative on the movie, a movie we saw, or 
some book. So I did it on the movie Midnight Cowboy.

20:36.760 --> 20:39.780
And after all the critique that she had given me, 
she came back, and I loved it, the movie was great,

20:43.760 --> 20:47.060
and I came back with an A. And, I mean, that just gave 
me the confidence that I needed and it made me feel

20:51.040 --> 20:53.060
great. And so it really helped me pick up a lot of my 
feeling about, feeling good about myself and that

21:01.040 --> 21:04.060
I was going to do well in school. My history 
professor, Alan Ashcraft. Alan Ashcraft? Alan

21:11.130 --> 21:13.150
Ashcraft was my history professor. And he was 
funny, he was joyful, he was a delight to listen to,

21:19.130 --> 21:23.150
and he really made history come alive. Did he have a 
nickname? You know how students gave it,

21:25.340 --> 21:27.360
everybody? No. I didn't know of one if he had one. 
No, no, no. But he had a very interesting mannerism

21:31.340 --> 21:34.360
about how he talked. He was a big fella, but he had a 
very soft way of talking and, no, but he, of course,

21:41.340 --> 21:44.360
in those days using the word damn and hell was not 
very common in public schools, but when he used it,

21:48.340 --> 21:50.360
it just made the class, the word came in at the right 
time. You took, do you remember how many hours you

21:52.340 --> 21:56.360
took that first semester? First semester I think I 
took 13 hours. 13. And you did okay in terms of?

22:01.340 --> 22:02.238
Yeah. I think I made like a, I came out with a, 2.8, 
2.9 maybe, I can't remember. Did you, you weren't

22:08.340 --> 22:11.360
in the Corps. No. Did you get involved in any Aggie 
activities that fall? That fall semester I did not

22:16.340 --> 22:20.360
because I was working. What I would do, I'd have my 
classes Mondays, Wednesdays, Fridays in the

22:22.340 --> 22:24.360
morning, and then at 2 o'clock in the afternoon, I 
would work at Alinko. So, and I would work from,

22:32.340 --> 22:36.770
from 2 to 10 in the evening, and that was my routine, 
so. And then what did you do on Tuesday, Thursday?

22:40.566 --> 22:41.770
Tuesday and Thursday I'd study. Oh, okay. And I'd 
go work, but I would study, but. So you were working

22:46.699 --> 22:49.770
three eight-hour days, or three eight-hour 
shifts, Monday, Wednesday, Friday? Monday,

22:56.420 --> 22:58.440
Wednesday, Friday, Oh, oh, so you worked a full, a 
full week. Yeah, a full time was because my oldest

23:03.420 --> 23:07.440
brother, Mike, when he was like 25, he and Andrew 
decided to help my parents, and they purchased a

23:13.420 --> 23:16.440
home for my parents. And the way it worked, it was 
that the boys and the girls, we would all pay for the

23:19.420 --> 23:21.440
house. So, as we became of age at 18, we would all 
pick up the slack. So it just worked out

23:26.420 --> 23:28.440
beautifully, because we were responsible for 
paying the mortgage and the utilities for a house.

23:32.420 --> 23:34.440
And then, of course, anything else, we bought it, 
if we bought our car, which I decided to buy me a car

23:37.420 --> 23:38.441
later. All of that was up on us, so we had to be 
working in order to meet the obligation of the

23:40.420 --> 23:46.440
house and utilities, which nowadays is hardly 
anything, but in those days it was, it was enough.

23:51.530 --> 23:53.550
Now, do you remember what your A&M bill was? Do you 
remember what a semester cost? I'm thinking

23:55.530 --> 23:58.530
something like, hmm, three or four hundred 
dollars. I mean, I really don't remember. And you

24:04.340 --> 24:05.361
paid that yourself? Yes. Yes. And how did you get to 
the campus that first semester? The first

24:11.390 --> 24:14.410
semester, I ended up, my dad had a, oh no, I ended up 
going with my brothers. I ended up going with my

24:20.510 --> 24:21.531
brothers, because we were going to class, we all 
had to, my other brother Moises had to also meet,

24:31.340 --> 24:33.360
we worked together at the same place. So we would 
set up our classes, Monday, Wednesday, Fridays,

24:36.340 --> 24:38.360
in the morning, and then we would drive. The year 
later, the summer, the summer of 1970 is when I

24:40.340 --> 24:44.360
bought me a, my own vehicle, a used vehicle, and 
then from there I had my own schedule. And what

24:48.340 --> 24:54.120
advice did those older brothers give you about 
being a college student? Well, you know, it's

24:56.150 --> 25:00.170
interesting because the advice was just 
something that had been given all the time. It's

25:00.150 --> 25:02.170
almost like, it was expected, and they would ask 
how they're going. And, but my oldest brothers by

25:05.150 --> 25:10.170
that time were married and gone. They were living 
in Houston. And so at home, it was only those of us

25:15.150 --> 25:19.170
that were still in school. Because every time one 
of the brothers graduated, they would move out. My

25:24.150 --> 25:25.171
oldest sister, my oldest sister lived in Bryan. 
She was married. And my other sister had moved to

25:29.150 --> 25:33.170
California. And my youngest sister, she worked 
here on campus, but later on finished her degree at

25:37.150 --> 25:40.170
A&M. So she was the only sister that finished Texas 
A&M. But they didn't tell you about, don't take

25:45.150 --> 25:47.170
this course or use? No, no, it was pretty much, you 
know, I guess we didn't talk much about what, what

25:55.210 --> 25:57.230
to expect or not expect, because we pretty much 
knew that it was, just get in there and do it. All

26:01.210 --> 26:02.026
right. Did you know, were your rules of conduct and 
behavior as a college student? Because of your

26:08.330 --> 26:10.350
family and? Well, I guess I, I always respected 
A&M. I respected the traditions. Those were just,

26:19.330 --> 26:22.350
I mean, I grew up not walking on the grass. I grew up 
not putting a cap on. I grew up, you know, singing

26:24.330 --> 26:28.350
the Aggie War Hymn, the Spirit of Aggieland. So all 
those things were just a part of me. To me, it was

26:31.330 --> 26:34.720
just like another extension of, of what it was to be 
a person, a human being, an American. I mean, and

26:39.700 --> 26:41.720
so, in that way, it was quite unique. I think 
respecting my elders, I mean, all that was very

26:46.700 --> 26:51.810
much an expectation. We'd see some students who 
were perhaps on the, on the fringe of the hippie,

26:56.790 --> 26:59.810
but really, but as hippies they got was that they 
got, they had long hair, but it wasn't, I think, to

27:01.790 --> 27:05.810
the extreme that you would see in either campus 
across the state. All right. But then in your

27:06.280 --> 27:07.810
private life, what were the rules that you knew you 
were to follow? Well, I pretty much had to, this

27:13.790 --> 27:18.810
being my home and my parents being Christian, my 
parents, I never, this may sound strange, but

27:21.790 --> 27:26.810
drinking was never one of those things that I had 
ever had aspired to, or it was just not one of those

27:26.790 --> 27:27.811
things, or smoking, or, or doing drugs. It was just 
never one of those things that I never thought

27:30.790 --> 27:36.510
about doing in a serious way. And, and I guess what 
helped a lot was that the people I hung around with,

27:41.490 --> 27:43.510
neither did they. What about what hours of the 
night you were to be home? Well, my dad, once we were

27:50.490 --> 27:51.511
18, pretty much it was really up to us. But during 
the day, during the week hours, we were working. So

27:56.490 --> 27:57.511
we'd get home about 10, 10 30. And we were, maybe 
study a little while, and eat, and then go to bed,

28:02.490 --> 28:03.511
and get up the next day. They would be, they would 
be, my dad, I hardly ever saw him except on, on

28:07.490 --> 28:08.511
Saturdays and Sundays. Because we were. Yeah. He 
was in completely different schedules. So I

28:12.490 --> 28:13.511
didn't see him. He would get up early in the morning 
and go to work. And then I was working when he got

28:15.490 --> 28:17.510
back. And so my mom was the one that was, who would 
give us breakfast and then leave us something to

28:19.490 --> 28:23.510
eat at night. But she was the one that we would 
always talk with. All right. That first fall, you

28:28.490 --> 28:32.510
said you went to Yale practice. Did you go to any 
silver taps? Yes. Yes. Went to silver taps. What

28:40.490 --> 28:43.510
was your impression at your first silver taps? I 
guess it was pretty,

28:49.660 --> 28:51.680
I guess I had never seen something like that. I 
related that to, wow, this is some solemn stuff

28:53.660 --> 28:57.680
that we do at church. Or something that, you know, 
this is, I guess what struck me was that it was

29:00.660 --> 29:03.730
students who were, who were engaged in this very 
solemn

29:03.710 --> 29:11.980
ritual that struck me, you know, regardless of 
what you were doing 30 minutes before, you know,

29:15.960 --> 29:17.980
when it came, everybody's quiet in a very 
meditative, you know, meditating kind of a mood.

29:22.960 --> 29:28.980
And I think that's what began to connect the dots 
for me about, A&M and its traditions. You know, you

29:30.960 --> 29:32.980
begin to, you go through the traditions and you see 
them and you hear them as a young kid. But when you

29:36.960 --> 29:39.980
begin to see these things all sort of fall in line, 
they all make a lot of sense. Did you go to fish camp?

29:42.960 --> 29:43.710
No. I don't even know if they had fish camp in the 
19th. They didn't. Yeah, they didn't. Cause I used

29:48.384 --> 29:51.980
to go up there to speak about what land grant 
education was. I was not one of them. Did you have

29:53.960 --> 29:57.980
anything to do with bonfire? No, I didn't because 
like I said, I was working. Did you, did you attend

30:01.960 --> 30:03.980
bonfire? Oh yes. In fact, my, my wife, my date, my 
